body: To solve this issue, we need to upgrade protobuf to the latest, which is a not released version yet. So the operation has a risk. @faxu, please consider it and make a decision whether we want to fix this issue now, or delay it a few months.
@snnn when is this planned to be released in protobuf?

Hi @paulvid , it's out of our control.  Protobuf is owned by Google. 
Before having it, you may:
1. in your local branch, update the protobuf module to the latest upstream version
2. In onnxruntime's cmake folder, open CMakeLists.txt and add a line of 
```
  list(APPEND onnxruntime_EXTERNAL_LIBRARIES atomic)
```
This line of code should be just before 
```
list(APPEND onnxruntime_EXTERNAL_LIBRARIES ${CMAKE_DL_LIBS} Threads::Threads)
```

The second step may not be necessary.

@christian-vorhemus does the suggested solution work for you to fix it just in a local fork? We don't plan to pick up a non-official release version of protobuf, but when they release the next version that includes the fix, we can update.

issue.title: ARM32v7 Cross Compile Broken due to protobuf Bug

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
Protobuf introduced a bug which causes the following error on ARM32v7 builds of onnxruntime (via [dockerfile](https://github.com/Microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/dockerfiles/Dockerfile.arm32v7)):

`libprotobuf.a(arena.cc.o): in function google::protobuf::internal::ArenaImpl::Init():
arena.cc:(.text+0x24): undefined reference to __atomic_fetch_add_8`

The following commit fixes the above problem:
[https://github.com/protocolbuffers/protobuf/commit/55ed1d427ccc0d200927746329ac9b811dee77b9](https://github.com/protocolbuffers/protobuf/commit/55ed1d427ccc0d200927746329ac9b811dee77b9)

Request: please bump onnxruntime's protobuf submodule to a newer version that includes the above fix.

body: I just tried to build onnxruntime by using the latest protobuf version 3.9.1 [which apparently fixed the compatibility issue](https://github.com/protocolbuffers/protobuf/releases/tag/v3.9.1). There is a new error coming up but it seems to be unrelated to protobuf, will look closer into it and potentially open a new issue.
I'll close it when our protobuf version is upgraded to 3.9.1
